txt_negFacts.title: Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: The province is named after Lake Ontario, a term thought to be derived from Ontarí:io, a Huron (Wyandot) word meaning "great lake", or possibly skanadario, which means "beautiful water" in the Iroquoian languages. Ontario has about 250,000 freshwater lakes.

txt_negFacts.title: Greenwood Lake
txt_negFacts.fact: Jasper Francis Cropsey created several paintings of Greenwood Lake beginning in 1843. Cropsey painted many paintings of the area such as American Harvesting (1864), Greenwood Lake (1870), Fisherman's House, Greenwood Lake (1877), and Cooley Homestead–Greenwood Lake (1886).

txt_negFacts.title: Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: The province is named after Lake Ontario, a term thought to be derived from Ontarí:io, a Huron (Wyandot) word meaning "great lake", or possibly skanadario, which means "beautiful water" in the Iroquoian languages.

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: The Trent-Severn Waterway for pleasure boats connects Lake Ontario at the Bay of Quinte to Georgian Bay (Lake Huron) via Lake Simcoe. The Oswego Canal connects the lake at Oswego to the New York State Canal System, with outlets to the Hudson River, Lake Erie, and Lake Champlain.

txt_negFacts.title: Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: In the northeastern parts of Ontario, extending south as far as Kirkland Lake, the cold waters of Hudson Bay depress summer temperatures, making it cooler than other locations at similar latitudes. The same is true on the northern shore of Lake Superior, which cools hot, humid air from the south, leading to cooler summer temperatures.

txt_negFacts.title: The Valley of Wyoming
txt_negFacts.fact: The Valley of Wyoming is an 1865 painting by American painter Jasper Francis Cropsey. Cropsey, a prominent landscape painter, rendered Valley so as to depict the Wyoming Valley in Northeastern Pennsylvania.

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: Lake Ontario is the easternmost of the Great Lakes and the smallest in surface area (7,340 sq mi, 18,960 km2), although it exceeds Lake Erie in volume (393 cu mi, 1,639 km3). It is the 13th largest lake in the world.

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: The Great Lakes Waterway connects the lake sidestream to the Atlantic Ocean via the Saint Lawrence Seaway and upstream to the other rivers in the chain via the Welland Canal and to Lake Erie. The Trent-Severn Waterway for pleasure boats connects Lake Ontario at the Bay of Quinte to Georgian Bay (Lake Huron) via Lake Simcoe.

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: The Oswego Canal connects the lake at Oswego to the New York State Canal System, with outlets to the Hudson River, Lake Erie, and Lake Champlain. The Rideau Canal, also for pleasure boats, connects Lake Ontario at Kingston to the Ottawa River in downtown Ottawa, Ontario.

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: In 1632 and 1656, the lake was referred to as Lac de St. Louis or Lake St. Louis by Samuel de Champlain and cartographer Nicolas Sanson respectively (likely for Louis XIV of France) In 1660 Jesuit historian Francis Creuxius coined the name Lacus Ontarius.

txt_negFacts.title: Hattie Tavernier
txt_negFacts.fact: Hattie and her family move to Albert Square in the summer of 1990. The head of the Tavernier household, Celestine (Leroy Golding), is a strict, religious man and despite having a strong personality, Hattie is made to obey his rules.

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: Also impacted by lake-effect snow is the Tug Hill Plateau, an area of elevated land about 20 miles (32 km) east of Lake Ontario. The "Hill", as it is often referred to, typically receives more snow than any other region in the eastern United States.

txt_negFacts.title: Balsam Lake (Ontario)
txt_negFacts.fact: The lake is the highest point of the Trent–Severn Waterway at 256.3 metres (841 ft); from here, the waterway descends to Georgian Bay in the northwest, and to Lake Ontario in the southeast. It is the highest point to which a vessel can be navigated from sea level in the Great Lakes-Saint Lawrence River drainage basin.

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: Nearly all of Lake Ontario's islands are on the eastern and northeastern shores, between the Prince Edward County headland and the lake's outlet at Kingston, underlain by the basement rock found throughout the region.

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: Some Lake Ontario areas of concern include the Oswego River and Rochester Embayment on the American side, and Hamilton Harbour and Toronto on the Canadian side. By the 1960s and 1970s, the increased pollution caused frequent algal blooms to occur in the summer.

txt_negFacts.title: Lake Ontario
txt_negFacts.fact: The city of Syracuse is 40 miles (64 km) inland, connected to the lake by the New York State Canal System. Over 2 million people live in Lake Ontario's American watershed.

txt_negFacts.title: Space Shuttle
txt_negFacts.fact: Its three-part fuselage provided support for the crew compartment, cargo bay, flight surfaces, and engines. The rear of the orbiter contained the Space Shuttle Main Engines (SSME), which provided thrust during launch, as well as the Orbital Maneuvering System (OMS), which allowed the orbiter to achieve, alter, and exit its orbit once in space.

txt_negFacts.title: Space Shuttle Atlantis
txt_negFacts.fact: STS-71 marked a number of firsts in human spaceflight: 100th U.S. crewed space flight; first U.S. Shuttle-Russian Space Station Mir docking and joint on-orbit operations; and first on-orbit change-out of shuttle crew. When linked, Atlantis and Mir together formed the largest spacecraft in orbit at the time.

txt_negFacts.title: Space Shuttle Columbia disaster
txt_negFacts.fact: The Space Shuttle Columbia disaster was a fatal incident in the United States space program that occurred on February 1, 2003, when the Space Shuttle Columbia (OV-102) disintegrated as it reentered the atmosphere, killing all seven crew members. The disaster was the second fatal accident in the Space Shuttle program, after the 1986 breakup of Challenger soon after liftoff.

txt_negFacts.title: SpaceX Dragon
txt_negFacts.fact: SpaceX undertook several U.S. Government contracts to develop the Dragon 2 crewed variant, including a Commercial Crew Development 2 (CCDev 2) - funded Space Act Agreement in April 2011, and a Commercial Crew integrated Capability (CCiCap) - funded space act agreement in August 2014.

txt_negFacts.title: SpaceX Dragon
txt_negFacts.fact: In 2005, NASA solicited proposals for a commercial ISS resupply cargo vehicle to replace the then-soon-to-be-retired Space Shuttle, through its Commercial Orbital Transportation Services (COTS) development program. txt_negFacts.title: Seven Pillars of Wisdom
txt_negFacts.fact: The title comes from the Book of Proverbs (Proverbs 9:1): "Wisdom hath builded her house, she hath hewn out her seven pillars" (King James Version). Prior to the First World War, Lawrence had begun work on a scholarly book about seven great cities of the Middle East, to be titled Seven Pillars of Wisdom.

txt_negFacts.title: Five Pillars of Islam

txt_negFacts.title: Marlton House
txt_negFacts.fact: Marlton House, or the Hotel Marlton as it was known for most of its existence, is located at 5 West 8th Street between Fifth and Sixth Avenues, in the Greenwich Village neighborhood of Manhattan, New York City. It is notable for having housed many famous artistic figures, especially during the peak of the area's bohemian scene.

txt_negFacts.title: 8th Street and St. Mark's Place
txt_negFacts.fact: Marlton House at 3–5 West 8th Street between Fifth and Sixth Avenues in Greenwich Village was built in 1900 as the Marlton Hotel, a single room occupancy (SRO) facility. It was notable for its bohemian clientele, but since 1987 it has been used as a dormitory for The New School.

txt_negFacts.title: Marlton House
txt_negFacts.fact: WritersThe Marlton Hotel attracted many writers and poets, most notably members of the Beat Generation, attracted to Marlton's location in the vibrant creative community of Greenwich Village.

txt_negFacts.title: Marlton House
txt_negFacts.fact: The Marlton Hotel was built in 1900 and, for much of its existence, served as a single room occupancy (SRO) hotel for mostly transient guests. However, many guests stayed for months or years at a time.

txt_negFacts.title: Five Pillars of Islam
txt_negFacts.fact: The religious practice of Islam, which signifies "submission to God", depends on fundamentals that are known as the Five Pillars. Each of the five pillars is alluded to in the Quran, though in various chapters (suwar).

txt_negFacts.title: Room and pillar mining
txt_negFacts.fact: Pillars known as barrier pillars separate the panels. The barrier pillars are significantly larger than the "panel" pillars and are sized to allow them to support a significant part of the panel and prevent progressive collapse of the mine in the event of failure of the panel pillars.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower
txt_negFacts.fact: The Eiffel Tower ( EYE-fəl; French: tour Eiffel [tuʁ‿ɛfɛl] (listen)) is a wrought-iron lattice tower on the Champ de Mars in Paris, France. It is named after the engineer Gustave Eiffel, whose company designed and built the tower.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: They later realize that Eiffel developed the tower to trap ghosts, making the Eiffel Tower the world's largest "ghost containment unit". By story's end, the ghosts were transmitted to the Ghostbuster's Primary Containment Unit back in New York, essentially de-haunting the Tower.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower
txt_negFacts.fact: Graffitists were also catered for: sheets of paper were mounted on the walls each day for visitors to record their impressions of the tower. Gustave Eiffel described some of the responses as vraiment curieuse ("truly curious").

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: In the 2010 computer-animated comedy film Despicable Me, the Eiffel Tower is shown being projected by the French Army and a mime after the Great Pyramid of Giza is stolen by Vector. Later on, Gru shows the Minions that they accomplished in stealing the tower, albeit the replica from Paris Las Vegas.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: The plot of Night of the New Magicians from the Magic Tree House book series by Mary Pope Osborne had the protagonists searching the 1889 World's Fair beneath the newly constructed Eiffel Tower for Alexander Graham Bell, Louis Pasteur, Thomas Edison, and Gustave Eiffel, who had all gathered atop the tower.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: The tower is seen in Eurotrip, and mentioned when a protagonist asks whether they should "check out the huge line at the Eiffel Tower".

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: In a commitment ceremony Erika Eiffel, an American woman, "married" the Eiffel Tower; her relationship with the tower has been the subject of extensive global publicity.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: 2011 In the 2011 Disney computer-animated film Cars 2, the Eiffel Tower appears "carified" and is different from the real life tower.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: In a Bill Nye the Science Guy episode titled "Magnetism", Bill Nye mentions two examples of "very tall metal towers" and the first one is the Eiffel Tower. The tower is shown onscreen when he mentions it.

txt_negFacts.title: List of the 72 names on the Eiffel Tower
txt_negFacts.fact: On the Eiffel Tower, 72 names of French scientists, engineers, and mathematicians are engraved in recognition of their contributions. Gustave Eiffel chose this "invocation of science" because of his concern over the protests against the tower.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower
txt_negFacts.fact: The tower is painted in three shades: lighter at the top, getting progressively darker towards the bottom to complement the Parisian sky. It was originally reddish brown; this changed in 1968 to a bronze colour known as "Eiffel Tower Brown".

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: 2013 The Eiffel Tower is featured and parodied in the Kickstarter-funded low-budget animated feature film, Dick Figures: The Movie, based on and apart of the animated web series, Dick Figures. The very top of the tower is where the second piece of the ancient sword the main characters set out to retrieve is.

txt_negFacts.title: Westgate Las Vegas
txt_negFacts.fact: Westgate CEO David Siegel was hoisted to the top of the hotel's sign the following day to begin removing the letters "LVH" to make way for the property's new name, Westgate Las Vegas.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower (Paris, Texas)
txt_negFacts.fact: The tower was constructed in 1993. It is a scale model of the Eiffel Tower in Paris, France, and is less than one tenth of the height of the original.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower in popular culture
txt_negFacts.fact: The film Category 7: The End of the World opens with the Eiffel Tower. The tower is ripped off its foundation and toppled by the tornado that hits Paris at the beginning of the film.

txt_negFacts.title: Eiffel Tower
txt_negFacts.fact: The mayor of Blackpool, Sir John Bickerstaffe, was so impressed on seeing the Eiffel Tower at the 1889 exposition that he commissioned a similar tower to be built in his town.

txt_negFacts.title: Organ stop

txt_negFacts.fact: All birds of the family Anatidae (ducks, geese, and swans) have a nail, a plate of hard horny tissue at the tip of the beak.

txt_negFacts.title: Beak
txt_negFacts.fact: The size and shape of the beak can vary across species as well as between them; in some species, the size and proportions of the beak vary between males and females. This allows the sexes to utilize different ecological niches, thereby reducing intraspecific competition.
